Problem Statement
In a futuristic world, each node in a Time-Locked Network is protected by a special ChronoString. A ChronoString is a string consisting of lowercase English letters. The time to decode a ChronoString is equal to the sum of the positions of its letters in the alphabet (a = 1, b = 2, ..., z = 26).

You are given an undirected graph with N nodes and M edges. Each node contains one ChronoString. Each edge has a time delay T which adds to the overall traversal time.

You start at node start and need to reach node end. When you enter a node for the first time, you must pay the decoding time of its ChronoString. You can only decode a node once.

Your task is to determine the minimum total time (decoding + traversal) required to reach the destination. If it is not possible to reach the destination, print -1.

Input Format
The first line contains two integers N and M — the number of nodes and edges.

The next N lines each contain a string Sᵢ — the ChronoString of node i.

The next M lines each contain three integers u, v, and T — representing an undirected edge between node u and v with traversal time T.

The last line contains two integers — the starting node start and destination node end

Output Format
An integer representing the minimum total time required to go from start to end.
If unreachable, output -1.

Constraints
1 ≤ N ≤ 10^4

0 ≤ M ≤ 2×10^4

1 ≤ U, V ≤ N

1 ≤ T ≤ 1000

1 ≤ |Sᵢ| ≤ 100

Sᵢ contains only lowercase English letters. 

1 ≤ start, end ≤ N

